Cross River State governor, Prof. Ben Ayade, has approved the sum of N500 million for the state’s newly inaugurated COVID-19 Response Team. The team which was inaugurated yesterday by Ayade at the open field of the Governor’s Office,  Calabar, was also given 20 vehicles for its operations. The mandate of the Response Team, according to the governor is to safeguard the state against the global scourge. Ayade used the opportunity to appeal to the federal government to give special treatment to the state as a result of its strategic border location. He said: “Cross River is an international border state, and with the incident in Cameroon, I call on President Muhammadu Buhari, the minister of Health to treat Cross River in a very peculiar way. We need the obvious and express attention of the federal government.” The goernor charged the team headed by the commissioner for Health, Dr. Betta Edu, to work assiduously to ensure that all preventive measures against the spread were adhered to. Ayade thereafter  announced the release of N500 million and 20 vehicles to support the activities of the Response Team, saying it was the desire of his administration to ensure that Cross River remained COVID-19-free.